  "prompt": "I have a dandruff problem. I wash my hair every other day, which makes my hair dry. If not washed, my scalp becomes oily, and dandruff and hair loss increase. What should I do?",
  "response": "Dealing with dandruff and balancing scalp health can be tricky, especially when washing too often dries out your hair, but not washing leads to oiliness, dandruff, and hair loss. Here\u2019s a structured approach to address your concerns:\n\n### 1. **Choose the Right Shampoo**\n   - **Anti-Dandruff Shampoos**: Look for shampoos containing active ingredients like ketoconazole, zinc pyrithione, selenium sulfide, or salicylic acid. These help reduce dandruff and control scalp oiliness.\n   - **Moisturizing Shampoos**: If your hair gets dry, alternate with a gentle, moisturizing shampoo to prevent further dryness.\n   - **Frequency**: Use the anti-dandruff shampoo 2\u20133 times a week and a moisturizing shampoo on other days.\n\n### 2. **Condition Properly**\n   - Apply conditioner only to the lengths and ends of your hair, avoiding the scalp. This prevents excess oil buildup while keeping your hair hydrated.\n\n### 3. **Scalp Care**\n   - **Scalp Exfoliation**: Use a gentle scalp scrub or a product with salicylic acid to remove dead skin cells and reduce flakiness.\n   - **Scalp Treatments**: Consider using serums or oils (like tea tree oil) that target dandruff and soothe the scalp. Apply sparingly and massage gently.\n\n### 4. **Adjust Your Washing Routine**\n   - Experiment with washing your hair every two days but use a gentle, sulfate-free shampoo to avoid stripping natural oils.\n   - If your scalp feels oily between washes, use a dry shampoo to absorb excess oil without over-washing.\n\n### 5. **Hydrate Your Hair**\n   - Use a deep conditioning mask or leave-in conditioner once a week to restore moisture and prevent dryness.\n\n### 6. **Lifestyle and Diet**\n   - **Hydration**: Drink plenty of water to keep your scalp and hair hydrated.\n   - **Diet**: Include foods rich in omega-3 fatty acids (like fish, flaxseeds, and walnuts) and vitamins (like B-complex and zinc) to support scalp health.\n   - **Stress Management**: Stress can worsen dandruff and hair loss. Practice relaxation techniques like yoga or meditation.\n\n### 7. **Avoid Irritants**\n   - Minimize the use of heat styling tools and harsh chemical treatments, which can dry out your scalp and hair.\n   - Avoid touching your scalp excessively, as this can transfer oils and dirt.\n\n### 8. **Consult a Dermatologist**\n   - If the problem persists, consult a dermatologist. They can assess your scalp condition, rule out underlying issues (like seborrheic dermatitis or fungal infections), and prescribe medicated treatments if needed.\n\nBalancing scalp health and hair hydration requires patience and consistency. Tailor your routine to what works best for your scalp and hair type.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
